heir column.\n- The **Separation Rule** requires that if **r2c4** is shaded, **r8c4** must be unshaded.\n\n---\n\n### **Step 9: Uniqueness Rule for r7c5**\n- **r5c5** and **r7c5** share the same symbol in their column.\n- Applying the **Uniqueness Rule**, only one of them can remain unshaded. Since **r5c5** is unshaded, **r7c5** must be shaded.\n\n---\n\n### **Step 10: Identifying the Contradiction**\nAt this point:\n- **r8c4**, **r8c6**, and **r7c5** are all shaded.\n- This creates a problem for **r8c5**, which is adjacent to both **r8c4** and **r8c6**. According to the **Separation Rule**, **r8c5** cannot be completely surrounded by shaded cells (Unshaded Neighbor Lemma).\n- Additionally, shading **r7c5** disrupts the connectivity of unshaded cells in the grid.\n\n---\n\n### **Conclusion**\nThe assumption that **r3c1** is unshaded leads to a contradiction. Therefore, **r3c1** must be shaded to maintain compliance with all Hitori rules.",
